#DESCRIPTION
#Representation of function as a power series
#ENDDESCRIPTION

#KEYWORDS('Power Series'  )

DOCUMENT();        # This should be the first executable line in the problem.

loadMacros(
"PG.pl",
"PGbasicmacros.pl",
"PGchoicemacros.pl",
"PGanswermacros.pl",
"PGauxiliaryFunctions.pl"
);

TEXT(&beginproblem);
$showPartialCorrectAnswers = 1;

$a = random(1,10,1);

BEGIN_TEXT

The function 
	\( f(x) = $a x \ln(1 + x) \)
is represented as a power series $BR 
	\( \displaystyle f(x) = \sum_{n=0}^\infty c_n x^n .\) $BR
Find the FOLLOWING coefficients in the power series. $BR

\( c_2 = \) \{ans_rule(20)\}  $BR
\( c_3 = \) \{ans_rule(20)\}  $BR
\( c_4 = \) \{ans_rule(20)\}  $BR
\( c_5 = \) \{ans_rule(20)\}  $BR
\( c_6 = \) \{ans_rule(20)\}  $BR

Find the radius of convergence \( R \) of the series. $BR 
\( R = \)  \{ans_rule(20)\}  . $BR

END_TEXT

#@ans=();
$ans0 =  $a/1;
$ans1 =  -1*$a/2;
$ans2 =  $a/3;
$ans3 =  -1*$a/4;
$ans4 =  $a/5;
$ans5 =  1;

#&ANS(std_num_cmp_list(@ans) );
#&ANS(ordered_num_cmp_list(@ans) );
&ANS(std_num_cmp($ans0) );
&ANS(std_num_cmp($ans1) );
&ANS(std_num_cmp($ans2) );
&ANS(std_num_cmp($ans3) );
&ANS(std_num_cmp($ans4) );
&ANS(std_num_cmp($ans5) );

&SOLUTION(EV3(<<'EOT'));

$SOL  $BR  $BR

Since \( \displaystyle \ln(1-x) = - \sum_{n=1}^\infty \frac{x^n}n \) by example #6 on p.748,
we also therefore have \( \displaystyle \ln(1+x) = - \sum_{n=1}^\infty \frac{(-x)^n}n \).
Thus
\[
\begin{align*}
$a x \ln(1+x)
&=	-$a \sum_{n=1}^\infty \frac{(-x)^n x}n	\\\\
&=	$a \sum_{n=1}^\infty \frac{(-x)^{n+1}}n	\\\\
&=	\frac{$a x^2}1 - \frac{$a x^3}2 + \frac{$a x^4}3 - \cdots
\end{align*}
\]
and so 
\( c_0 = 0 \), \( c_1 = 0 \), \( c_2 = $a \), \( c_3 = \frac{-$a}2 = $ans1 \),
\( c_4 = \frac{$a}3 = $ans2 \), and in general,
\( c_n = \frac{$a(-1)^n}{n-1} \) for all \( n \geq 2 \).

EOT

ENDDOCUMENT();        # This should be the last executable line in the problem.

